         <div type="jest" xml:id="COUR15">
            <byline resp="#DERR1"><persName>Luke Derr</persName></byline>
            <div type="old">
               <head><title><persName type="primary">Tarltons</persName> answere to a <persName
                        type="man">Noblemans</persName> question.</title></head>
               <ab>THere was a <persName type="man">Nobleman</persName> that asked <persName
                     type="primary">Tarlton</persName> what he thought of <persName type="men"
                     >Souldiers</persName> in time of peace? Marry quoth he, they are like
                     <objectName type="building">Chimneyes</objectName> in Summer.</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="modern">
               <head><title>TITLE-MODERNIZED</title></head>
               <ab>There was a nobleman that asked Tarlton what he thought of soldiers in time of
                  peace? He says, they are like chimneys in summer.</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="endnote">
               <p/>
            </div>
         </div>
         <div type="jest" xml:id="COUR16">
            <byline resp="#DERR1"><persName>Luke Derr</persName></byline>
            <div type="old">
               <head><title><persName type="primary">Tarltons</persName> Iest to an vnthriftie
                        <persName type="court">Courtier</persName>.</title></head>
               <ab>THere was an vnthriftie <persName type="court">Gallant</persName> belonging to
                  the <orgName type="court">Court</orgName> that had borrowed <objectName
                     type="value">fiue pounds</objectName> of <persName type="primary"
                     >Tarlton</persName>, but hauing lost it at <placeName type="city"
                     >Dice</placeName>, hee sent his man to <persName type="primary"
                     >Tarlton</persName> to borrow <objectName type="value">fiue pounds</objectName>
                  more, by the same <objectName type="value">token</objectName> he owed him already
                     <objectName type="value">fiue pounds</objectName>: pray tell <persName
                     type="man">your Master</persName>, quoth <persName type="primary"
                     >Tarlton</persName>, that if he will send me the <objectName type="value"
                     >token</objectName>, I will send him the <objectName type="value"
                     >money</objectName>: for who deceiues me once, <persName type="god"
                     >God</persName> forgiue him: If twice, <persName type="god">God</persName>
                  forgiue him: but if thrice, <persName type="god">God</persName> forgiue him, but
                  not me, because I could not beware.</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="modern">
               <head><title>TITLE-MODERNIZED</title></head>
               <ab>There was a deadbeat Gallant belonging to the Court that had borrowed five pounds
                  from Tarlton, but having lost it at Dice, he sent his man to Tarlton to borrow
                  five pounds more, already owing him five pounds: tell your master, says Tarlton,
                  that if he will send me the token, I will send him the money: someone who deceives
                  me once, god forgive him: If twice, god forgive him: but three times, god forgive
                  him, but not me, because I could not beware.</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="endnote">
               <p/>
            </div>
         </div>
         <div type="jest" xml:id="COUR17">
            <byline resp="#DERR1"><persName>Luke Derr</persName></byline>
            <div type="old">
               <head><title>How <persName type="primary">Tarlton</persName> flouted two <persName
                        type="court">Gallants</persName>.</title></head>
               <ab><persName type="primary">TArlton</persName> being in a <state type="anger"><desc>mery
                     vaine</desc></state>, as he walked in the <placeName type="city">great Hall in
                     Gréenwitch</placeName>, he met my <persName type="man">old Lord
                     Chamberlain</persName>, going betwéene two fantasticke
                     <persName>gallants</persName>, &amp; cryed aloud vnto him, <persName type="man"
                     >my Lord</persName>, <persName type="man">my Lord</persName>, you goe in <state
                     type="danger"><desc>great danger</desc></state>: whereat amazed, hee askt whereof: of
                  drowning (quoth <persName type="primary">Tarlton</persName> ) were it not for
                  those two bladders vnder ech of your <objectName type="body"
                  >armes</objectName>.</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="modern">
               <head><title>TITLE-MODERNIZED</title></head>
               <ab>Tarlton being in a bad mood, as he walked in the great hall in Greenwitch, he met
                  my old Lord Chamberlain, going between two fantastic gallants, and cryed aloud
                  onto him, my lord, my lord, you go in great danger: amazed, he asked where: if not
                  for those two blades under each of your arms.</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="endnote">
               <p/>
            </div>
         </div>

         <!-- The following jest appears in the City section -->

         <div type="jest" xml:id="CITY01">
            <byline resp="#DERR1"><persName>Luke Derr</persName></byline>
            <div type="old">
               <head><title><persName type="primary">Tarltons</persName> Iest of a red <objectName
                        type="body">face</objectName>.</title></head>
               <ab>T O an Ordinary in the <orgName type="friers">White Friers</orgName>, where
                  Gentlemen vsed, by reason of extraordinarie dyet, to this <persName type="primary"
                     >Tarlton</persName> often frequented, as well to continue acquaintance, as to
                  please his appetite: it chanced so vpon a time (especially) being set amongst the
                  Gentlemen and Gallants, they enquired of him why <state type="sad"
                     ><desc>melancholy</desc></state> had got the vpper-hand of his mirth, to which he said
                  little, but with a squint <objectName type="body">eie</objectName>, as custom had
                  made him <trait><desc>hare eied</desc></trait>, he lookt for a Iest to make them <state
                     type="happy"><desc>merry</desc></state>; at last he espyed one that sate on his left side,
                  which had a <trait type="color"><desc>very red</desc></trait>
                  <objectName type="body">face</objectName>, hee being a <state type="great"><desc>very
                     great</desc></state> Gentleman (which was all one to <persName type="man"
                     >Tarlton</persName> ) he presently in great hast called <persName type="man"
                     >his Hoast</persName>: who do I serue my <persName type="man">Hoast</persName>?
                  quoth <persName type="primary">Tarlton</persName>, the <persName type="woman"
                     >Quéenes Maiestie</persName>, replied the good man of the house: how happens it
                  then quoth <persName type="primary">Tarlton</persName>, that to her <persName
                     type="woman">Maiesties</persName> disgrace, you dare make me a companion with
                     <persName type="man">Seruingmen</persName>, clapping my <persName type="man"
                     >Lord Shandoyes Cullisance</persName> vpon my sléeue, looking at the Gentleman
                  with the <trait type="color"><desc>red</desc></trait>
                  <objectName type="body">face</objectName>, me thinks quoth he, it sits like the
                  Sarazens <objectName type="body">head</objectName> without Newgate: the Gentlemans
                  Salamanders face <trait type="color"><desc>burnt</desc></trait>▪ like Aetna for <state
                     type="anger"><desc>anger</desc></state>, the rest laughed <state type="happy"
                     ><desc>heartily</desc></state>: in the end all <state type="anger"><desc>inraged</desc></state>, the
                  Gentleman swore to fight with him at the next méeting.</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="modern">
               <head><title>TITLE-MODERNIZED</title></head>
               <ab>To an ordinary in the White Friers, where gentlemen used, by reason of
                  extraordinaire diet, to this Tarlton often frequented, as well to continue
                  acquaintance, as to please his appetite: it chanced so upon a time (especially)
                  being set amongst the gentlemen and gallants, they asked him why sadness overtook
                  his happiness, to which he said little, but squinting, he looked for a jest to
                  make them happy; at last he found one on his left side, which had a very red face,
                  he being a very great gentleman he presently in great confidence called his host:
                  who I serve as my host? Tarlton said, the Queen’s Majesty, replied the good man of
                  the house: how is that Tarlton says, to her Majesties disgrace, you dare make me a
                  companion with servingmen, clapping my Lord Shandoyes upon my sleeve, looking at
                  the gentleman with the red face, he says, it sits like the Sarazens head without
                  Newgate: the Getlemans Salamanders face burnt like Aetna for anger, the rest
                  laughed: in the end all enraged, the gentleman swore to fight him at the next
                  meeting. </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="endnote">
               <p/>
            </div>
         </div>
